equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives isoleucine selection through late-layer MLP convergence
equation_narrative.story: Position 30 in ubiquitin sits in a hydrophobic environment with 8 structural contacts, predominantly aliphatic. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation consistent with small-to-medium hydrophobic residues, with the logit lens fluctuating between alanine, leucine, and threonine as different structural and chemical features accumulate. The representation remains diffuse until layer 23, when leucine leads at 23%. The decision crystallizes in layers 27-33: isoleucine-specific MLP neurons activate strongly (N31:2817 projects 1.065, N32:2085 projects 0.851), driving I from 6% at L23 to 93% at L33. Valine briefly competes at L29-31 (peaking at 30%) but is suppressed by late-layer MLPs that distinguish branched-chain specificity.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 gather structural and chemical context from 8 nearby positions. Attention heads at L20 (head 16, 1.684 projection) and L12 (head 1, -1.49 projection) read structural contacts, establishing a hydrophobic-leaning representation. Early features (F1:5480, F1:9146, F1:1508) encode local sequence context around the KAKIQD motif. By L9, features like F9:5728 (58.85 projection) and F9:1281 (54.34 projection) consolidate hydrophobic character. The logit lens shows high volatility—lead changes every 1-2 layers—reflecting the model's exploration of compatible hydrophobic residues (A, L, T all peak above 20%). Co-evolutionary signal is minimal (only 2 coupled positions), so the representation is dominated by local structural chemistry rather than distant functional constraints.
perception_phase.context_character: The biochemical context by L23 is a buried hydrophobic core environment with aliphatic contacts. The representation is consistent with medium-sized nonpolar residues, with leucine leading at 23% but alanine, valine, and threonine all viable in the logit lens.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 8 residues within contact distance, predominantly hydrophobic (consistent with ubiquitin's compact core)
L20 head 16: strong structural writer (0.921 structural attention, 1.684 projection) consolidates hydrophobic environment
L12 head 1: structural eraser (-1.49 projection, 0.775 structural attention) refines against incompatible polar/charged residues
Co-evolutionary signal: minimal (2 positions), indicating local structural constraint dominates over distant functional coupling

decision_phase.summary: The decision phase begins at L24 with isoleucine at only 6%, but accelerates dramatically in L27-33. Layer 27 MLP neurons (N27:3282 projects 0.728) initiate the shift, and L31-32 MLPs provide decisive support: N31:2817 (1.065 projection) and N32:2085 (0.851 projection) are strong I-specific writers. Attention heads at L31 (head 8, 1.725 projection) and L32 (head 1, 1.393 projection) reinforce the decision. Valine competes briefly (peaks at 30% at L31) but is suppressed by MLP neurons N30:4595 (-1.2 projection) and N31:3219 (-0.711 projection) that distinguish I from V based on subtle side-chain geometry.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, the representation shifts from encoding hydrophobic context to selecting among specific branched-chain residues. L24 features (F24:3692, F24:9151) begin to activate prediction channels, though probabilities remain diffuse (L at 23%, I at 6%, V at 6%). By L27, isoleucine-specific neurons activate and the model commits to the I/V/L competition.

candidates.narrative: Isoleucine emerges decisively in layers 27-33 after being nearly absent earlier (6% at L23). The breakthrough occurs at L31-32 with highly specific MLP neurons: N31:2817 projects 1.065 (top vote for I), N32:2085 projects 0.851, and N32:4433 projects 0.792. SAE features at L30 (F30:5919, 21.83 projection) and L33 (F33:4166, 89.38 projection; F33:6423, 87.33 projection) encode I-specific prediction channels. I rises from 16% at L29 to 37% at L30 to 93% at L33, reflecting late-layer convergence on the correct branched-chain isomer for this buried core position.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L27, accelerates L30-31, dominant by L32 (93% final)

L31 head 8 (1.725 proj, 0.674 structural attention) — structural writer reinforcing I

candidates.narrative: Valine is a strong competitor in the decision phase, peaking at 30% at L31 before collapsing to 5% at L33. V benefits from shared branched-chain chemistry with I and receives support from N29:1603 (0.707 projection, though top vote is for V at 0.969). However, V is actively suppressed by late-layer erasers: N30:4595 projects -1.2 (top vote for W/L, not I), and N31:3219 projects -0.711. The model ultimately distinguishes I from V based on subtle geometric differences in the beta-branched side chain, with I's additional methyl group better fitting the local packing constraints.

candidates.narrative: Leucine dominates the logit lens in the perception phase, peaking at 29% at L25 and leading from L8-L26. This reflects the representation's hydrophobic character as structural contacts are read—L is the most common aliphatic residue, so a generic 'buried hydrophobic' representation projects toward L in the logit lens. However, this is NOT the model predicting leucine; it's an artifact of the representation's chemical character. L collapses in the decision phase (23% at L23 → 15% at L29 → 2% at L33) as I-specific and V-specific neurons activate, distinguishing beta-branched residues from linear chains.
candidates.key_layers: Leads L8-L26 (peaks 29% at L25), declines L27+ as decision sharpens
key_evidence: F9:5728 (58.85 proj) and F9:1281 (54.34 proj) — early attention features encoding hydrophobic context

N24:2791 (-0.643 proj, top vote for F) and N25:2161 (-0.409 proj) begin suppressing L in decision transition

candidates.narrative: Alanine appears prominently in the early logit lens (20% at L0, peaks 27% at L20) because the representation is hydrophobic-leaning and alanine is the smallest hydrophobic residue. The logit lens projects toward A when the model encodes 'small and nonpolar' features from local sequence and structural contacts. However, A is never a serious candidate in the decision phase—it drops to 13% at L23 and 0.13% at L33. The perception-phase prominence is purely a lens artifact: the model is building a representation of a buried hydrophobic position, not guessing alanine.

candidates.narrative: Threonine peaks at 21% at L13, reflecting a brief period where the representation includes polar character—possibly from reading nearby charged residues (K29, D32) in the local sequence. T's hydroxyl group makes it compatible with both hydrophobic packing and hydrogen bonding, so it appears in the logit lens when the model is integrating mixed signals. However, T is suppressed in the decision phase by neurons that enforce strict hydrophobicity: N25:2228 projects -0.35 (top vote for T at 0.516, but net eraser), and T drops to 0.46% by L33.

turning_points.description: The representation consolidates hydrophobic character as structural contacts are read. L8 sees leucine take the logit-lens lead (26%), and L10 shows a velocity event (+3.41 total delta, both attention and MLP contributing) that strengthens aliphatic features. However, L10-L13 also shows competition between L, A, and T (T peaks at 21% at L13), reflecting the model's integration of both hydrophobic packing and nearby polar residues (K29, D32). This volatility is characteristic of perception-phase exploration, not decision uncertainty.

The representation shifts from generic hydrophobic to branched-chain-compatible. L19 MLP neurons (N19:4997 projects 0.638, N19:2904 projects 0.622) write strongly toward I, and L20 head 16 (1.684 projection, 0.921 structural attention) consolidates structural context. Alanine peaks at 27% at L20, then declines as the model refines toward medium-sized aliphatics. By L23, leucine leads at 23%, but I, V, and A are all within 7-13%, indicating the representation is primed for branched-chain selection but not yet committed.

The decision crystallizes as isoleucine-specific neurons activate. L27 head 4 (1.488 projection, low structural attention) and N27:3282 (0.728 projection, top vote for T at 0.82 but also strong for I) initiate the shift. L28 attention (+6.24 delta, attention-driven) and L30 MLPs drive I from 16% to 37%. Critically, N30:4595 projects -1.2 (top votes for W/L), actively suppressing valine and leucine. This is where the model commits to isoleucine over other branched-chain residues, distinguishing beta-branched geometry from linear chains.

Final convergence on isoleucine through MLP and attention synergy. L31 head 8 (1.725 projection, 0.674 structural attention) writes strongly, and N31:2817 (1.065 projection, top vote for I) provides decisive MLP support. Valine peaks at 30% at L31 but is immediately suppressed by N31:3219 (-0.711 projection). L32 MLPs (N32:2085 at 0.851, N32:4433 at 0.792) and attention (head 1 at 1.393, head 3 erasing at -1.251) finalize the decision. I reaches 93% by L33, with SAE features F33:4166 (89.38 projection) and F33:6423 (87.33 projection) encoding the final I-specific prediction.

deep_dives.label: Structural attention L12-L20
deep_dives.caption: L12 head 1 erases incompatible residues (-1.49 projection, 0.775 structural attention), while L20 head 16 writes hydrophobic context (1.684 projection, 0.921 structural attention). These heads read the 8 structural contacts and establish the buried core environment that constrains the decision space to aliphatic residues.

deep_dives.caption: L9 features (F9:5728 at 58.85, F9:1281 at 54.34) encode hydrophobic character from structural contacts. L18 features (F18:6256 at 17.98, F18:4071 at 17.37) refine toward medium-sized aliphatics. These features represent the biochemical context being assembled, not predictions.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision initiation L24-L27
deep_dives.caption: L24-L25 MLPs show net negative projection (total -2.48 and -1.87), suppressing leucine and alanine. L26-L27 MLPs (N27:3282 at 0.728) begin activating I-specific neurons. This is where the model transitions from representing 'hydrophobic core' to selecting 'isoleucine specifically'.

deep_dives.label: MLP convergence L29-L32
deep_dives.caption: L29-L32 MLPs drive the final decision. N31:2817 (1.065 proj) and N32:2085 (0.851 proj) are strong I-specific writers. N30:4595 (-1.2 proj) and N31:3219 (-0.711 proj) suppress valine. This is the decisive evidence: late-layer MLPs distinguish I from V based on beta-branched side-chain geometry.

deep_dives.label: SAE prediction channels L30-L33
deep_dives.caption: L30 features (F30:5919 at 21.83, F30:974 at 20.68) activate I-specific prediction channels. L33 features (F33:4166 at 89.38, F33:6423 at 87.33) encode the final output. These are high-specificity features that directly vote for isoleucine, distinct from the context-encoding features in earlier layers.

deep_dives.label: Velocity events L28-L32
deep_dives.caption: L28 (+6.24 delta, attention-driven), L29 (-4.47 delta, attention-driven), L31 (-6.71 delta, MLP-driven), and L32 (+6.84 delta, attention-driven) show the oscillation between I and V as the model refines its decision. The final L32 push is attention-driven, consolidating structural evidence for isoleucine.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts isoleucine by assembling a buried hydrophobic core context through layers 1-23, then activating I-specific MLP neurons in layers 27-33 that distinguish beta-branched geometry from linear aliphatic chains. The strongest evidence is the convergence of late-layer MLPs (N31:2817 at 1.065, N32:2085 at 0.851) and attention heads (L31 head 8 at 1.725, L32 head 1 at 1.393) that read structural contacts and enforce the precise side-chain packing requirements of this position. Valine competes briefly due to shared branched-chain chemistry, but is suppressed by neurons that encode the subtle geometric difference between I and V in tight hydrophobic environments.
